# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1776-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1776 Connecticut gubernatorial election** took place on April 11, 1776; the offices to be filled were governor and lieutenant governor.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1776-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] This was the only such election to take place before Connecticut approved the Declaration of Independence on October 10, 1776.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1776-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Statesman Jonathan Trumbull won the election.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1776-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Trumbull had been governor of the Connecticut Colony prior to the American Revolution.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1776-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The candidate for Lieutenant Governor in 1776 was Matthew Griswold, who also won his election.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1776-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Trumbull went on to win successive gubernatorial elections until 1784, when he was succeeded by Griswold.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1777-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1777 Connecticut gubernatorial election** was held on April 10, 1777, in order to elect the Governor of Connecticut.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1777-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull won re-election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1777-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The exact number of votes cast in this election is unknown.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1777-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 10, 1777, incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull easily won re-election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1777-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Trumbull was sworn in for his second term on May 10, 1777.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1778-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1778 Connecticut gubernatorial election** was held on April 9, 1778, in order to elect the Governor of Connecticut.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1778-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 9, 1778, incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull easily won re-election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1778-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Trumbull was sworn in for his third term on May 10, 1778.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1779-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1779 Connecticut gubernatorial election** was held on April 8, 1779, in order to elect the Governor of Connecticut.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1779-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 8, 1779, incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull easily won re-election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1779-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Trumbull was sworn in for his fourth term on May 10, 1779.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1780-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1780 Connecticut gubernatorial election** was held on April 13, 1780, in order to elect the Governor of Connecticut.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1780-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull won a plurality of the vote in his re-election bid against other candidates.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1780-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] However, as no candidate received a majority of the total votes cast as was required by Connecticut law, the election was forwarded to the Connecticut legislature, who chose Trumbull as governor.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1780-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 13, 1780, incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull won re-election after having been chosen by the Connecticut legislature.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1780-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Trumbull was sworn in for his fifth term on May 10, 1780.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1781-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1781 Connecticut gubernatorial election** was held on April 12, 1781, in order to elect the Governor of Connecticut.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1781-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 12, 1781, incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull won re-election after having been chosen by the Connecticut legislature.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1781-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Trumbull was sworn in for his sixth term on May 10, 1781.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1782-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1782 Connecticut gubernatorial election** was held on April 11, 1782, in order to elect the Governor of Connecticut.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1782-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull won a majority of the vote in his re-election bid against other candidates.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1782-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 11, 1782, incumbent Nonpartisan Governor Jonathan Trumbull won re-election against other candidates.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1782-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Trumbull was sworn in for his seventh term on May 10, 1782.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] A presidential election was held in Connecticut on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1788–89 United States presidential election.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] The Connecticut General Assembly chose seven electors, all Federalists, who voted for George Washington.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Washington was widely expected to be the first choice of the Electoral College in the first elections held under the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Some uncertainty persisted concerning the choice of the first vice president, however, due partly to the electoral system established by Article II of the Constitution.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Under this system, each elector voted for two candidates; the candidate with the largest majority was elected president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] With Washington likely to become president, many observers expected John Adams, the U.S. ambassador to the United Kingdom, to receive the other vote of most of the electors.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Some, such as Alexander Hamilton, feared Adams's popularity would be so great as to result in a tied vote, throwing the election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Hamilton believed this event would be deeply embarrassing to the new government.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Through his associate, Samuel Blachley Webb, Hamilton personally intervened with the electors to urge them not to vote for Adams.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Hamilton's appeal persuaded two unknown electors to withhold their votes from Adams, who received five votes from Connecticut to Washington's seven.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] The Council and the House of Representatives met separately on January 7 to conduct the election.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] The House nominated seven electors, of whom five were accepted without debate.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] The Council attempted to replace Thaddeus Burr and Jedediah Huntington with Abraham Davenport and George Wyllys on the list of electors, but withdrew its objection when the House refused to agree to the substitution.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] When the electors met in Hartford, Connecticut, on February 4, all seven electors voted for Washington.
[src:1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Five of the seven also voted for Adams, but at Hamilton's urging, two electors instead voted for the governor of Connecticut, Samuel Huntington.
